01:47.900 --> 01:50.600
So just keep that in mind. You can start here.

01:50.600 --> 01:52.900
This is if you're learning React for the first time

01:52.900 --> 01:55.400
that you are in the correct place.

01:55.400 --> 01:58.000
If you're also kind of sharpening your React skills,

01:58.000 --> 01:59.400
you're also in the right place.

01:59.400 --> 02:01.400
So let's just talk about how I want to teach this course to you.

02:01.400 --> 02:03.500
I'm a first principles teacher.

02:03.500 --> 02:06.200
That's just the style that resonates with me,

02:06.200 --> 02:08.800
and therefore it's the way that I try and teach other people.

02:08.800 --> 02:12.500
The idea there being we're going to start by writing React with no tools.

02:12.500 --> 02:16.500
It's just going to be like a script tag on an HTML page.

02:16.500 --> 02:18.700
And then we're going to slowly add tools as we go along,

02:18.700 --> 02:21.700
as we hit barriers of complexity.

02:21.800 --> 02:25.800
I do this because if you just jump straight into the full toolset,

02:25.800 --> 02:28.300
you, one, don't understand what's going underneath the hood.

02:28.300 --> 02:31.000
It makes it hard to debug, and you learn to resent your tools

02:31.000 --> 02:36.300
because tools are complex, but they also add ease.

02:36.300 --> 02:38.500
And if you just get the ease and you don't understand the complexity

02:38.500 --> 02:44.600
that it's solving, you resent the tool for the complexity that it adds.

02:44.600 --> 02:46.200
So that's my methodology.

02:46.200 --> 02:48.600
If you don't like it, you're still stuck on this ride with me.

02:48.600 --> 02:52.200
So bear with me.

02:52.200 --> 02:53.700
Who is this course for?

02:53.700 --> 02:56.000
I'm hoping it's for you.

02:56.000 --> 03:01.900
But it's for people looking to get started in React or deepen the React skills.

03:01.900 --> 03:05.700
This should probably not be the first time you're writing JavaScript.

03:05.700 --> 03:10.300
