07:59.100 --> 08:06.600
What's your opinion on the react team not recommending plain react anymore using next JS?

08:06.600 --> 08:08.200
That's a good question.

08:08.200 --> 08:12.700
There was a some controversy about this and we'll probably go over this more kind of throughout the day.

08:12.700 --> 08:16.600
But there was some controversy around that the react docs just go straight.

08:16.600 --> 08:19.500
It was like just use remix or next or something like that.

08:19.500 --> 08:22.600
And they kind of shied people away from using client side react.

08:22.600 --> 08:24.400
I think it's personally extremely misguided.

08:24.400 --> 08:29.800
I've been writing client side react for a decade and I've done okay for myself.

08:29.800 --> 08:39.100
And the sites that I've worked on have been plenty fast and plenty responsive without any concept of react server side components.

08:39.100 --> 08:47.200
My thought is that the react team is solving for massive enterprise problems like Facebook sized problems,

08:47.200 --> 08:52.600
Netflix sized problems, and most of us don't have those problems, right?

08:52.600 --> 08:56.800
Client side react does plenty well by itself.

08:56.800 --> 09:03.800
And so I think it's 100 percent viable to ship client side react without even having a concept of next JS.

09:03.800 --> 09:06.900
I'm not at all disparaging next JS or remix or any of those.

09:06.900 --> 09:09.100
I also think they're extremely valuable for what they do.

09:09.100 --> 09:12.600
But if you don't have those shape of problems, then you shouldn't use that shape of tool.

